body:
### Code

```Rust
fn main() {
    let mut foo = Some(0u8);

    while let Some(bar) = foo {
        if bar == 3 {
            foo = Some(0);
            break;
        } else {
            foo = Some(bar + 1);
        }
    }

    // some code here requiring `bar < 3`
}
```


### Current output

```Shell
Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
warning: value assigned to `foo` is never read
 --> src/main.rs:6:13
  |
6 |             foo = Some(0);
  |             ^^^
  |
  = help: maybe it is overwritten before being read?
  = note: `#[warn(unused_assignments)]` on by default

warning: `playground` (bin "playground") generated 1 warning
    Finished dev [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 1.30s
     Running `target/debug/playground`
```


### Desired output

```Shell
Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
    Finished dev [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.89s
     Running `target/debug/playground`
```


### Rationale and extra context

Insertion of the `break` after the assignment of `Some(0)` to `foo` causes the warning to be emitted, even though it is being read at the beginning of the `while let` loop.

### Other cases

```Rust
fn main() {
    let mut foo = Some(0u8);

    while let Some(bar) = foo {
        if bar == 3 {
            foo = Some(0);
            // break;
        } else {
            foo = Some(bar + 1);
        }
    }

    // some code here requiring `bar < 3`, now always executed 
}
```

